<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="704" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="7.[809,1452,1745,1865]" pageId="7" pageNumber="704">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[809,933,1745,1769]" pageId="7" pageNumber="704">Etymology.</emphasis>
The name 
<taxonomicName box="[1043,1189,1745,1769]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pseudopimelodidae" genus="Microglanis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageId="7" pageNumber="704" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="xylographicus">
<emphasis box="[1043,1189,1745,1769]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="704">xylographicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is derived from the Greek 
<emphasis box="[809,864,1777,1801]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="704">xylos</emphasis>
referring to wood, and 
<emphasis box="[1134,1242,1777,1801]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="704">graphikos</emphasis>
, of writing. It is a reference to the horizontally striated color pattern, like a tree bark. An adjective.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="705" pageId="7" pageNumber="704" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="7.[809,1452,1905,1961]" lastBlockId="8.[136,779,179,555]" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="705" pageId="7" pageNumber="704">
